>  Personally I dislike null checks and usually try to ensure objects floating around are not null and have noticed they are not prevalent in the code base BUT, often the checks do serve a needed purpose.

I like them when it causes fail fast.  For example the following code would not fail fast.  Adding a null check would fail fast.

```java
void setItems(List items) {
  // If null, this code may fail later when something tries to use this.item.. would be nicer to get 
  // a stacktrace for the code calling set
  this.items = items;
}
```

If the function is using the passed in argument a NPE would naturally happen w/o an explicit null check. 

> Note my comment on the collections assumed "not null". 

Assuming not null is fine because the collection is being used and you would get a NPE at that point if it were null.

The `SecurityOperation` class is currently an internal only class. If this interface were to represent something like we have today, it should look something more like:

```java
public interface Security {
  void initialize(SiteConfiguration configuration);
  Authenticator authenticator();
  Authorizor authorizor();
  PolicyChecker policyChecker(); // or PermissionsHandler
}
```

I don't think we need the second layer interface, `SecurityOperation` if we're going to re-design the pluggable security.

Also, if this does become proper SPI, it should use a more generic configuration type (`Properties`?), or a special purpose one (`SecurityConfiguration`?) rather than expose our internal `SiteConfiguration` configuration class.

I like having this in SPI under a security package: ```org.apache.accumulo.core.spi.security```

Then use ```org.apache.accumulo.core.spi.common.ServiceEnvironment``` as a parameter like so:

```java
public interface SecurityModule {
/**
   * Only called when Accumulo is initiazed.  This will initialize the security for Accumulo.
   *
   * @param configuration SiteConfiguration server configuration
   */
  void initialize(ServiceEnvironment env);

  Authenticator authenticator();
  PolicyChecker policyChecker(); // or PermissionsHandler

}
```

I am not convinced we need an ```Authenticator``` and an ```Authorizor```.  If we initialize all the security and server side user creds in the initialize method then we can just handle all the authentication stuff with the Authenticator.  Or just have one thing checking permissions and authentication.  There seems to be a lot of duplicate code across all three of our current pluggable interfaces.  There are some methods like: `dropUser, cleanUser and initUser` which will happen after Intialization, where there might be some overlap.
